faqs:
  - q: "When is a Whippet considered senior?"
    a: "Whippets are long-lived for their size — many reach 12–15 years — so they cross into 'senior' later than most breeds, usually around 9–10. As a lean, athletic sighthound they often stay sprightly well into old age, so don't go by a birthday: watch for a greying muzzle, a slower recovery after a run, stiffer mornings, and — the one to catch early in this breed — a creeping loss of muscle and condition over the topline and hindquarters. Because a Whippet carries so little spare fat, that condition slips away faster and more visibly than in a stockier dog."
  - q: "How much should I feed a senior Whippet per day?"
    a: "Often about the same as — or even slightly more, per kilo, than — you might expect, because the senior risk in this breed is under-feeding, not over. An adult Whippet (9–19kg) eats roughly 180–280g of dry food a day; a calmer senior burns a little less, but a fast metabolism and thin fat reserves mean you rarely need to cut as hard as you would for a Labrador. As a rough June-2026 guide, feeding a 14kg senior as its sole diet costs about £0.55–0.95/day on quality grain-free kibble, £0.85–1.30/day air-dried, or £1.40–2.30/day on fresh-cooked subscription. Judge by condition, not the chart: you should always see a hint of the last ribs and a tucked waist — but the muscle over the spine and hips should stay full."
  - q: "My senior Whippet is losing weight — should I worry?"
    a: "Some loss of muscle over the topline and back legs is normal ageing (sarcopenia), and a Whippet shows it sooner because there's no fat to hide it. But sudden or ongoing weight loss in an older dog is a red flag worth a vet visit — dental pain, kidney or heart disease, and several other senior conditions all cause it, and a sighthound's lean baseline means there's little margin. Once a vet has ruled out illness, the dietary answer is calorie density and palatability: a richer, highly-digestible food fed in a volume a narrow chest can handle, split across the day, so an ageing dog with a smaller appetite still takes in enough."
  - q: "What should I look for in food for an older Whippet?"
    a: "Five things, and the priorities flip from a typical senior guide. First, calorie density and quality fat — a small, rich meal maintains condition without forcing big volumes onto a deep, narrow chest. Second, generous named-meat protein (aim for 28%+) to fight the muscle loss that's so visible on a lean frame; the 'less protein for old dogs' line is an outdated myth unless a vet has diagnosed kidney disease. Third, easy digestibility for a fast gut that's often sensitive. Fourth, omega-3 for the thin, low-cover skin and coat — and ageing joints. Fifth, a soft or small-kibble texture, because Whippets are prone to dental disease and worn or missing teeth make crunchy biscuit a chore."
  - q: "Why is keeping weight ON the goal for a senior Whippet, when most senior advice is about slimming down?"
    a: "Because most senior-dog advice is written for breeds that gain weight easily — Labradors, Cockers, retrievers — where the ageing risk is obesity stressing arthritic joints. A Whippet is the inverse: built like a sprinter with almost no body fat, it's a breed where owners are routinely told their healthy dog 'looks too thin', and where genuine under-condition in old age is the real danger. Feeding guidance written for stockier dogs will under-feed a senior Whippet. The job here is to hold lean muscle and a little reserve, not to strip it away — while still keeping the dog truly lean by sighthound standards (ribs faintly visible, waist tucked)."
  - q: "Do senior Whippets have dental problems that affect feeding?"
    a: "Yes — Whippets, like many fine-boned breeds, are prone to dental disease, and by old age many have worn, loose or missing teeth. That makes a hard, dry kibble uncomfortable and can quietly suppress appetite, which is dangerous in a breed with no fat reserve. Softer formats — fresh-cooked, air-dried rehydrated with warm water, or a wet topper over kibble — are easier and more tempting for sore senior mouths. Keep up dental care, and mention any drooling, dropped food or reluctance to eat to your vet."
  - q: "Are there senior Whippet health quirks that affect food or medication?"
    a: "Two worth knowing, though neither is strictly dietary. Sighthounds are sensitive to anaesthesia (low body fat changes how drugs are distributed), which matters for any senior dental or surgical procedure — flag the breed to your vet. And many herding/sighthound lines carry the MDR1 gene variant affecting how certain drugs are processed; it doesn't change feeding, but it's a senior-health detail worth a test if you've never done one. On the food side, keep meals warm and draught-free in winter: a thin-coated, low-fat senior feels the cold badly and burns extra calories staying warm."
